          "slidetitle": "Securing Models on Device",
          "subtitle": "Protecting Models from Tampering and Theft",
          "slidecontent": "• On-device models stored as files can be copied, reverse-engineered, or modified without proper protection\n• Encryption at rest keeps model weights unreadable if a device is stolen or physically accessed\n• Secure boot ensures only authorised firmware and model versions can run on the hardware\n• Code signing verifies integrity\n• Tamper-evident logging records any unexpected access attempts or changes to model files\n• Hardware security modules (HSMs) provide a dedicated, isolated environment for storing encryption keys safely"
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "slidetitle": "Securing Models Against Tampering",
          "subtitle": "Protecting integrity from edge to core",
          "slidecontent": "• On-device models stored as files can be copied, modified, or replaced by attackers with physical access\n• Cryptographic signing verifies that a model has not been altered since it left the manufacturer\n• Tamper-evident hardware (such as secure enclaves) detects and blocks unauthorised changes at runtime\n• Encryption at rest keeps model weights unreadable if a device is stolen\n• Regular integrity checks catch silent corruption, whether accidental or deliberate\n• A compromised model may produce subtly wrong outputs without triggering any obvious system alert"
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "slidetitle": "Securing Edge AI Models",
          "subtitle": "Protecting Models from Tampering and Theft",
          "slidecontent": "• Edge AI models stored on factory devices are vulnerable to extraction, copying, and reverse engineering\n• Encryption at rest protects model weights if a device is physically stolen\n• Secure boot ensures only authorised firmware and models load on startup\n• Tamper-evident hardware (such as TPM chips) detects unauthorised access attempts\n• Access controls limit which users or processes can query or update a deployed model\n• Regular integrity checks confirm a model has not been silently modified between production runs"
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "slidetitle": "Securing Edge AI Deployments",
          "subtitle": "Protecting Models, Data, and Access",
          "slidecontent": "• Physical access controls to prevent tampering with edge devices on the factory floor\n• Encrypted model storage to stop intellectual property theft\n• Strict authentication for any remote updates or configuration changes\n• Network segmentation to isolate edge nodes from broader corporate systems\n• Regular vulnerability audits"
