      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to Edge AI in Production Lines. This course is all about how artificial intelligence is being used directly on the factory floor, and what that means in practice. Now, when most people think of AI, they imagine data being sent off to some distant server or cloud platform. But edge AI works differently. The intelligence lives right there on the machine, on the production line itself, making decisions in real time without needing any internet connection at all. That means if a fault appears, or a product moves out of tolerance, the system can react instantly, keeping everything running smoothly. No waiting, no delays. And that speed really does matter when you are talking about high-volume manufacturing. Now, it is not all straightforward. Bringing AI onto the factory floor also introduces some genuine security considerations that we need to take seriously. Throughout this course, we will explore all of these areas, so you come away with a solid, practical understanding of edge AI in production."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "So, what exactly do we mean when we talk about Edge AI? At its core, Edge AI simply means that the artificial intelligence is doing its work right there, on the device itself, rather than sending data off to a remote server or cloud platform somewhere. Think of it as putting the brain directly inside the machine. That might be a camera on the production line, a sensor monitoring temperature, or a piece of equipment tracking vibration. Because the processing happens locally, decisions can be made in a fraction of a second, without waiting for a round trip to the internet and back. And that matters enormously in a manufacturing environment where every millisecond counts. There is also a practical reliability benefit here. If your network goes down or your connection becomes unstable, an Edge AI system keeps working regardless, because it simply does not depend on that connection in the first place. That is the fundamental idea we will be building on throughout this course."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "Once your AI model is deployed onto an edge device, it becomes a physical asset that someone could potentially steal, copy, or tamper with. So how do we protect it? The first line of defence is encrypting the model at rest, meaning the model weights are scrambled and unreadable if someone gets hold of the device. We also use secure boot, which ensures the hardware will only run authorised firmware and approved model versions, nothing else. Code signing works alongside this by verifying that the model files themselves have not been altered. If anything suspicious does happen, tamper-evident logging keeps a record of unexpected access attempts, giving you a clear audit trail. And underpinning all of this are hardware security modules, or HSMs, which are dedicated chips designed specifically to store encryption keys in a safe, isolated environment. Together, these layers make it significantly harder for anyone to interfere with your deployed models."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "When you deploy an AI model onto a factory floor device, that model is essentially just a file sitting on a piece of hardware, and that makes it vulnerable. Someone with physical access could copy it, swap it out, or quietly modify it. So how do we protect against that? Well, there are several layers of defence working together. Cryptographic signing acts like a tamper-proof seal, confirming the model is exactly as the manufacturer intended. Secure hardware components, sometimes called secure enclaves, actively block any unauthorised changes while the system is running. If a device is stolen, encryption ensures the model weights remain completely unreadable. And regular integrity checks mean that even gradual, silent corruption gets caught before it causes problems. The really concerning scenario is a model that has been tampered with but still appears to be working fine, quietly producing slightly wrong outputs with no obvious alarm going off. That is why these protections need to be layered and continuous, not just a one-time check."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "Once you deploy an AI model onto a factory device, that model becomes a valuable asset worth protecting. Think of it like proprietary software or a trade secret sitting on hardware that could potentially be physically accessed by the wrong person. There are several layers of defence you can put in place. Encryption keeps the model's data safe if a device is ever stolen. Secure boot means the device will only run software that has been properly authorised, so nobody can sneak in a modified version at startup. Specialist hardware components, like TPM chips, can actually detect if someone has physically tampered with a device. On top of that, you can restrict which users or systems are even allowed to interact with the model in the first place. And finally, running regular integrity checks means you will quickly spot if a model has been quietly altered between production runs, before it causes any real damage."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "Security is something we absolutely cannot overlook when we're deploying Edge AI on a production line. Think about it: these devices are sitting right there on the factory floor, so the first thing we need to do is make sure nobody can physically tamper with them. Beyond that, the AI models running on those devices often represent significant intellectual property, so we store them in an encrypted format to keep them protected. When it comes to making updates or changes remotely, we want strict authentication in place, so only authorised personnel can make those modifications. We also practise network segmentation, which essentially means our edge devices live on their own isolated network, separate from the wider corporate systems. That way, if something goes wrong in one area, it doesn't spread. And finally, we carry out regular vulnerability audits to catch any weaknesses before they become serious problems. Security isn't a one-time job; it's an ongoing commitment."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "Before you roll out any Edge AI system on a production line, you really want to have a solid plan for managing risk. The first thing to do is test thoroughly in a controlled environment before anything goes live. You do not want to discover problems when machines are running at full capacity. Once your devices are deployed, keep their firmware up to date, because manufacturers regularly release patches that close security vulnerabilities. You should also be quite strict about who and what can access those devices. The fewer entry points, the smaller your attack surface. Beyond that, set up continuous monitoring so you can spot unusual behaviour in the outputs early on, rather than waiting for something to go wrong. And perhaps most importantly, plan for failure from the very beginning. Assume things will break at some point and have a recovery process ready. A little preparation now saves a great deal of disruption later."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So before we move on, let's just bring together the most important lessons from everything we've covered. First, your AI models need regular updates, because the world on your production line changes, and your models need to keep up. Make sure any data processed on the device is encrypted, keeping it secure right where it lives. Always keep an eye on model drift, because a model that performed brilliantly last month might quietly be losing accuracy now. And please, test thoroughly in a controlled environment before you roll anything out at full scale. You also want to hold both security and processing speed in mind at the same time, because sacrificing one for the other will cause problems down the line. Finally, and this is perhaps the most practical piece of advice, start with a small pilot, learn from it, and then scale up gradually. Getting these fundamentals right gives you a really solid foundation for confident, reliable AI deployment in your facility."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
